Yep — you can stop using the system containerd service and make Docker use only its own storage under /mnt/data/docker, then redeploy.

Important detail (so you don’t get stuck): Docker internally uses containerd components, so on RHEL you usually should not uninstall the containerd.io package if Docker depends on it. What you want is to disable the system containerd service and remove Docker’s “external containerd socket” config.

Here’s the clean reset.

A) Stop everything
sudo systemctl stop docker docker.socket 2>/dev/null || true
sudo systemctl stop containerd containerd.service 2>/dev/null || true

B) Disable system containerd service (so Docker won’t talk to it)
sudo systemctl disable --now containerd 2>/dev/null || true
sudo systemctl mask containerd 2>/dev/null || true


Check it’s really inactive:

systemctl is-active containerd || true

C) Reset Docker to use /mnt/data/docker only

Edit /etc/docker/daemon.json to remove any "containerd": "unix:///run/containerd/containerd.sock" line.

Quick way: overwrite with a minimal correct config:

sudo mkdir -p /etc/docker
cat <<'EOF' | sudo tee /etc/docker/daemon.json
{
  "data-root": "/mnt/data/docker"
}
EOF

D) Clean the old containerd data on / (frees space)

Only do this after containerd is stopped/masked.

sudo rm -rf /var/lib/containerd
sudo rm -rf /etc/containerd


Also make sure the target path exists:

sudo mkdir -p /mnt/data/docker

E) Start Docker and verify it uses the right path
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl start docker
docker info | egrep -i 'Docker Root Dir|containerd'


